<protolog id="rid.4201_nm.9811" type="description" xmlns="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog file:/C:/NamesforLife/workspace/namesforlife-schema/protolog.xsd"><organism doi="10.1601/nm.9811" rank="genus">Citreicella</organism><reference id="rid.4201"><citation citation-type="journal"><authors><person-name><surname>Sorokin</surname><given-names>D.Y.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Tourova</surname><given-names>T.P.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Muyzer</surname><given-names>G.</given-names></person-name></authors><article-title>Citreicella thiooxidans gen. nov., sp. nov., a novel lithoheterotrophic sulfur-oxidizing bacterium from the Black Sea</article-title><year>2005</year><volume>28</volume><issue>8</issue><fpage>679</fpage><lpage>687</lpage><source id="121">Systematic and Applied Microbiology</source><abbrev>Syst Appl Microbiol</abbrev><issn>0723-2020</issn><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1016/j.syapm.2005.05.006</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">16261857</pub-id></citation></reference><content><p class="title"><s>Description of <em>Citreicella</em> gen. nov.</s></p><p class="etymology"><s><em>Citreicella</em> (<em>Cit.rei.cel′ la.</em> L. n. <em>citreum,</em> lemon; L. fem. n. <em>cella</em> cell; N. L. fem. n. <em>Citreicella</em> lemmon-shaped cell).</s></p><p class="description"><s>Cells are Gram-negative, nonmotile, usually lemon-shaped short rods.</s><s>Obligately aerobic and obligately heterotrophic.</s><s>Short-chain organic acids, hexoses, and aminoacids are utilized as carbon and energy source.</s><s>Oxidase and catalase positive.</s><s>Mesophilic and NaCl dependent.</s><s>The G+C content is 67.5–69.2 mol%.</s><s>Belong to the alpha-3 subdivision of the Proteobacteria.</s><s>The type species is <em>C. thiooxidans</em>.</s></p></content></protolog>